### Meaning

# Centering fixed the collinearity properly — all VIFs are now under 2, so these coefficients can be trusted individually. And the key result: for men, the centered linear temperature effect is significant (β = 6.54 seconds per °C above that course's average temperature, p = 0.016), while the quadratic term isn't (p = 0.163). That means there's no real curvature/optimum in this data — it's a straightforward monotonic relationship: hotter-than-typical race days are slower, cooler-than-typical are faster, across the whole range you have. Women show the same direction (positive coefficient) but it doesn't reach significance (p = 0.305).
## The genuinely interesting part is the sign flip between the two model versions. Without Marathon in the model, temp_c's coefficient is negative for both sexes (higher temp → seemingly faster times) — the opposite direction, though not significant either way. That's not noise, it's a real confounding pattern: courses like Berlin (fast, moderate temps) versus others create a spurious between-course association that runs backwards from the true physiological relationship. Once you control for which course it is and look only at within-course year-to-year temperature variation, the honest relationship re-emerges: heat slows elite men down, just like the sports science literature would predict. This is actually a nice, quotable methodological point for your report — a textbook Simpson's paradox, and proof the course fixed effects are doing real work rather than being competitive with temperature over the same variance.
### Write up: "No optimal-temperature curve was detected in this elite-only sample. However, controlling for course, men's average top-10 time increased significantly with above-typical race-day temperatures (+6.5s/°C, p = 0.016); no significant effect was found for women. This relationship reverses sign if course is not controlled for, reflecting confounding between which marathon is run and its typical weather — a caution for any elite marathon weather analysis that pools across courses without fixed effects."

